[{"id":"VR802602","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a cutaway view of a solenoid with a horizontal central axis. The current is coming out of the page at the top, and the current is going into the page at the bottom. A rectangular Amperian loop is drawn around part of the top half of the solenoid, and its sides are labeled from 1 to 4, counterclockwise from the bottom side.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR802602.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A long solenoid with a horizontal central axis has the current coming out of the page at the top and going into the page at bottom, as shown in a partial cut-away view. Also shown is a rectangular Amperian loop with sides labeled from <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> to <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"4\"><math alttext=\"4\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>4</mn></math></span></span>. Which of the following correctly identifies the side (or sides) of the rectangle that leads (lead) to a non-zero contribution to the line integral of the magnetic field over the Amperian loop?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR802602_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> only</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1\"><math alttext=\"1\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>1</mn></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"3\"><math alttext=\"3\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mn>3</mn></math></span></span> only</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"2\"><math alttext=\"2\" d